The start symbol S has only two possible productions:

1. S → NT468 NT206  
   NT206 derives the single terminal t0.  
   Since t0 does not appear in the target string, any derivation using this rule fails.

2. S → NT383 NT87  
   NT87 has the single rule NT87 → NT86 NT473, and NT473 ⇒ t285.  
   Therefore every string derived via this branch must contain the terminal t285.  
   The target string contains no occurrence of t285, so this branch also fails.

Because all derivations from the start symbol force a terminal (t0 or t285) that is absent from the given string, the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

To come from the start‐symbol S the derivation has to begin with one of the two rules that are provided for S: 

1. S → NT468 NT206  
2. S → NT383 NT87  

Rule 1 would force the single–terminal non‑terminal NT206 (which is defined only as NT206 → 't0') to appear somewhere in the final sentence.  
The string we are checking, however, contains no token t0 at all, so rule 1 is impossible.

Hence the grammar would have to use rule 2: S → NT383 NT87.  
If NT383 produced more than one terminal, its very first terminal would have to be the first word of the string (t77).  
The only binary expansion of NT383 is NT383 → NT85 NT129, whose leftmost terminal is necessarily the single token NT85 → 't199'.  
The only other possibilities for NT383 are direct terminal productions, but the only terminals it can produce directly are 't26' and 't158'.  
Thus NT383 can yield t199, t26 or t158 as its first (and, in the last two cases, only) terminal—but it can never yield t77.  
Consequently the sentence cannot begin with t77 if it is derived through rule 2.

Since rule 1 is impossible and rule 2 cannot generate a sentence whose first token is t77, the given 36‑token string cannot be derived from S.

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT468 NT206  
   NT206 immediately yields the terminal t0.  
   Therefore any sentence derived via this rule must end with the token t0.  
   The given string ends with t65, not t0, so this rule cannot be used.

2. S → NT383 NT87  
   Consider the left component NT383.  
   Its possible single–step expansions are  

   • NT383 → 't158'  (a single terminal)  
   • NT383 → 't26'   (a single terminal)  
   • NT383 → NT85 NT129

   – If NT383 chooses either single‑terminal rule, the very first token of the
     generated string would have to be t158 or t26.  
     The actual first token is t276, so these two options are impossible.

   – If NT383 chooses NT85 NT129, the first token still must be the single
     terminal generated by NT85.  
     NT85 has only the rule NT85 → 't199', so the first token would have to be
     t199—again contradicting the actual first token t276.

   Hence NT383 cannot generate the required initial portion of the given
   string, making the production S → NT383 NT87 impossible as well.

Since neither of the two productions for the start symbol S can lead to the
string, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

The start symbol S has only two possible productions:

1. S → NT468 NT206  
   (NT206 produces the single terminal “t0”, which does not appear anywhere in the target string, so this branch is impossible.)

2. S → NT383 NT87  
   NT383 can derive the single terminal “t158”, matching the first token of the string, so the remainder of the string (41 more tokens) would have to be derived entirely from NT87.

Examining the grammar, NT87 has exactly one production rule:

NT87 → NT86 NT473

• NT473 is a terminal‑producing symbol whose only terminal is “t285”.  
• The required string contains no occurrence of “t285”.  
• Because NT87 expands to exactly two symbols (NT86 followed by NT473), it can generate at most two terminals, never the 41 terminals that are still needed.

Therefore NT87 cannot generate the substring following “t158”, which means the whole string cannot be generated by the grammar.

Hence the given string is not in the language of the grammar.
